    "title": "The Complete Fault Journey",
    "objective": "Synthesize the external and internal components of the earth loop impedance path into a single explanation of the fault current journey.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Fault current must complete a full loop back to the supply transformer.",
      "The total impedance (Zs) consists of both external (Ze) and internal (R1 + R2) resistances.",
      "The MET serves as the connection point between these two sections."
    ],
    "questionText": "A fault occurs on a final circuit. Explain how the total earth loop impedance (Zs) is formed by describing the journey of the fault current through the specific external and internal components of the system.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Ze represents the external path from the transformer to the installation origin.",
      "R1 is the resistance of the line conductor carrying current to the point of the fault.",
      "R2 is the resistance of the CPC carrying current from the fault back to the MET.",
      "Zs is the total sum of these components: Ze + (R1 + R2)."
    ],
    "hint": "Trace the current from the transformer, through the line wire, through the earth wire, and back to the supplier's return path."
  }
}

